Python Programming: Task 3 - Exercises (Strings)
Questions and Problem Statements
Q1. Write a program to take a name as input and print it in reverse using string slicing.

Q2. Palindrome Check: Accept a string from the user and check if it reads the same forward and backward.

Q3. Take the string "How are you doing today ?" and replace all spaces with underscores (_).

Q4. Given the string "banana", count and print how many times the letter "a" appears.

Q5. Find and print the index of the first occurrence of the letter "a" in the word "banana".

Q6. Convert the string "openai" to all uppercase letters.

Q7. Take a string in all caps, such as "HELLO WORLD", and ensure it remains uppercase using the .upper() method.

Q8. Concatenate two separate string variables, "Hello" and "World", with a space between them.

Q9. Given the word "programming", remove all occurrences of the letter "m" and print the result.

Q10. String Slicing: Extract and print the characters from index 3 to 6 (inclusive) from the word "programming".

Q11. Calculate and print the total length (number of characters) of the string "Hello World".

Q12. In the string "hello_everyone", replace the word "everyone" with "there".

Q13. Replace all spaces in the sentence "hello world how are you" with hyphens (-).

Q14. Use a string method to remove leading and trailing whitespace from the string " messy text ".

Q15. Check if the string "Hi there " starts with the prefix "Hi" and print the boolean result.

Q16. Check if the string "I am running" ends with the suffix "ing" and print the boolean result.

Q17. Format the string "welcome to the jungle" so that only the first letter of the sentence is capitalized.

Q18. Joining Lists: Take the list ["I", "love", "coding."] and join the elements into a single string separated by spaces.

Q19. Convert the string "Python is fun" to lowercase and then replace all spaces with underscores.

Q20. Sentence Reversal: Split the string "Hello World Python" into words, reverse the order of the words, and join them back into a single string.

Q21. Convert the string "good morning world" to "Title Case" (where the first letter of every word is capitalized).

Q22. Count the total occurrences of the word "apple" in the string "apple banana apple mango apple".

Q23. Compare the first and last characters of the word "racecar" and print whether they are the same.

Q24. Advanced Slicing: Given the string "aXbYcZd", extract every second character starting from index 1.

Q25. Character Swap: Create a new string from "Tomorrow" where the first and last characters are swapped.

Q26. Insert a hash symbol (#) between every single character in the string "Tomorrow is holiday".

Q27. Data Cleaning: Remove the special characters @, !#, and $ from the string "he@llo!#wo$rld".

Q28. Compare the results of the .find() and .index() methods when searching for the letter "i" in "mississippi".

Q29. Remove all occurrences of the word "hello" from the string "hello world hello" and trim any remaining edge spaces.

Q30. Case Swapping: Convert all uppercase characters to lowercase and vice versa in the string "Hello WorLd".